Docker networking - linking containers and commands 

* Docker networking important allowing for implementation of micro services architecture *
* Microservices allow for different part of an app run as independent services each in its own container *
* Docker networking insures these containers can communicate efficiently and securely *
* easily scalable *

Docker provides default network options to link containers : 

1. Bridge network -> Containers connected on the bridge network can communicate with their own ip addresses on a private bridge network 
- Isolated from host machine’s network = provides extra  layer of security 

2. Host network -> in host mode the container uses the host machines network directly w/out isolation ( as if container plugged direct into host network) 
- Useful for containers that need to directly interact with the host system 

3. None network -> gives container no network interface at all 
- Means it is completely isolated 
- Ensures a container has no network access at all 
- Useful for certain networking scenarios 


